Thanks, hasather.<br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>MikeFoster wrote:</cite><br />I don't think it &quot;looks&quot; like it<br /></div></blockquote><br />Does <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://html5.ouvaton.org/valid.html">http://html5.ouvaton.org/valid.html</a><!-- m --> &quot;look&quot; like valid valid HTML 4.01 Strict? (It is: <a href="http://validator.w3.org/check?uri=http%3A%2F%2Fhtml5.ouvaton.org%2Fvalid.html&amp;ss" class="postlink">http://validator.w3.org/check?uri=http%3A%2F%2Fhtml5.ouvaton.org%2Fvalid.html&amp;ss</a>)<br /><br />Strictly speaking, a HTML document is not &quot;missing&quot; anything just because tags like &lt;body&gt;, &lt;html&gt; and &lt;/p&gt; are not indicated explicitly in the source; there's only one place to put them anyway (in a document conforming to the specification, that is), which has led to their being defined as strictly optional in any (at least reasonably &quot;recent&quot;) version of HTML (excluding XHTML, of course).<br /><br />HTML5 will disallow most of the uncommon constructions illustrated in <a href="http://html5.ouvaton.org/valid.html" class="postlink">http://html5.ouvaton.org/valid.html</a>, which means that a random valid HTML5 document, unlike a random valid HTML4 document (or XHTML 1.0 sent as text/html, I should add), is actually likely to be rendered correctly. As for the optional tags and quotes, these will remain optional, so there is no need to remove/add optional items or change one's coding habits. <br /><br />-- <br />&amp;<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=52">and</a> — Sat Mar 24, 2007 1:41 pm</p><hr />
